TICK-BORNE ENCEPHALITIS VIRUS - RUSSIA: (NOVOSIBIRSK REGION)
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Tue 5 May 2009
Source: epidemiolog.ru [translated by Mod. NP, edited]
<http://epidemiolog.ru/situation/index.php?ELEMENT_ID=2605>


As of 4 May 2009 the Novosibirsk region [Oblast] has reported 1135
inhabitants who have sought medical attention after having been
bitten by ticks. (Whereas by contrast in 2008 only 591 cases were
recorded). In total 367 of those were children (32 percent). A total
of 10 people have been hospitalised on suspicion of having contracted
tick-borne encephalitis virus infection.

The maximum numbers of tick bites were reported from the Iskitimsky,
Toguchinsky, and Novosibirsk districts, and from the city of Berdsk.
In the city of Novosibirsk the greatest numbers of tick bites were
recorded in the Soviet (38 percent), Pervomaisk (15 percent), and
Zaeltsovsky (14 percent) districts. A total of 25 inhabitants of the
Altay region of the Novosibirsk Oblast suffered from tick bites, and
one person in the Kemerovo region.

As a result of laboratory investigations tick-borne encephalitis
virus was found in 42 ticks (12 percent) taken from 346 tested. As of
4 May 2009 in the Novosibirsk region [Oblast] 11 5731 persons,
including 43 000 children up to the age of 18, have been vaccinated
against tick-borne encephalitis virus infection.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-RUS
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Tick-borne encephalitis is prevalent throughout southern Russia and
appears to be on the increase with greater abundance of ticks
following milder winter and spring weather. A map of the
administrative regions of Russia showing the location of the
Novosibirsk Oblast in the south can be accessed at:
<http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/37/Russian-regions.png>.
The city of Novosibirsk can be located using the HealthMap/ProMEDmail
interactive map at:
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?>. - Mod.CP]

